```yaml
review:
  document: <document identifier or path>
  reviewer: vmodel-skill-review-testspec
  date: <YYYY-MM-DD>

  verdict: <APPROVED | REJECTED | DESIGN_ISSUE>
  # Decision-table outcome — see SKILL.md "Verdict decision table".
  # Precedence: DESIGN_ISSUE wins over REJECTED, which wins over APPROVED.
  # The meta-gate routes per upstream-traceability: if
  # `check.spec-ambiguity-test.fail` fires AND the failure is upstream-
  # traceable (parent spec at the layer is itself ambiguous; governing ADR
  # missing the load-bearing decision; upstream Requirement or Product Brief
  # outcome under-specified), verdict is DESIGN_ISSUE. Otherwise REJECTED.

  inputs_provided:
    testspec_document: true
    parent_spec: <true | false>            # DD at leaf, Architecture at branch, Requirements + Product Brief at root
    governing_adrs: <true | false | partial>
    derived_from_artifacts: <true | false | partial>
  # When parent_spec is false, the layer's `verifies` resolution cannot be
  # verified — halt with `missing-inputs` rather than approve blind.
  # When governing_adrs is false-or-partial AND `governing_adrs:` is non-empty
  # AND specific entries do not resolve, halt with `missing-inputs`.

  perspectives_applied:
    - author              # case shape, oracle specificity, derivation strategies
    - layer-derivation    # parent-spec coverage at the appropriate seam
    - historian           # retrofit honesty — only when `recovery_status:` declared

  findings:
    # Zero or more findings, one per failed check.
    # Each follows finding.yaml.tmpl.
    - id: F-001
      case_id: <case id | "GLOBAL" | "FRONTMATTER">
      check_failed: <dotted catalog identifier>
      severity: <hard_reject | soft_reject | info>
      category: <shape | derivation | per-layer | case-quality | oracle | verifies | test-double | coverage-mutation | integration-system | retrofit | dd-traceability | architecture-traceability | requirements-traceability | meta-gate>
      evidence: |
        <verbatim quote or location reference from the artifact under review>
      recommended_action: |
        <generic pointer; never specific replacement wording>

    # ... more findings ...

  summary: |
    # 2-4 sentences. Cite the dominant findings, not every finding.
    # Verdict justification: which trigger fired, why DESIGN_ISSUE vs REJECTED if
    # applicable, whether all inputs were provided.
    # When DESIGN_ISSUE: name the upstream artifact (parent spec / governing ADR
    # / upstream Requirement / Product Brief outcome) that needs to revise before
    # this TestSpec can reach APPROVED.
    # When REJECTED for a hard-reject: name the refusal class (A / B / C /
    # coverage-mutation-section-missing / broken-reference).

  recommended_next_action: |
    # APPROVED  → "Proceed to test-code derivation against this TestSpec."
    # REJECTED  → "Hand findings to the matched author skill for rewrite."
    # DESIGN_ISSUE → "Escalate to <upstream artifact name>; rewriting this
    #                 TestSpec in place will not resolve the upstream gap."

  counts:
    hard_reject: <integer>
    soft_reject: <integer>
    info: <integer>
    design_issue: <integer>      # count of meta-gate findings; usually 0 or 1
```

## Notes for emitting the verdict

- `verdict` matches the decision table in SKILL.md exactly. Do not override.
- If the document is APPROVED but the review surfaced `info` findings, list them — they are useful observations even though they do not affect the verdict.
- The `summary` field should be the first thing a human reader sees. Aim for: *"Verdict: \<X>. Trigger: \<dominant cause>. Inputs: \<provided / partial / missing — implications>."*
- For DESIGN_ISSUE verdicts, name the upstream artifact in `summary` and `recommended_next_action`. Do not name the matched author skill explicitly — say "the matched author skill".
- For REJECTED verdicts triggered by a hard-reject finding, the `summary` names the refusal class so the consumer knows the shape of the rewrite:
  - A — fabricated retrofit intent (`title` / `notes` / reconstructed `verifies`)
  - B — orphan tests (`verifies` empty or unresolvable at artifact / case level)
  - C — weak assertion / unspecified oracle
  - coverage-mutation-section-missing — derived hard from the load-bearing QB group
  - broken-reference — `governing_adrs:` or `derived_from` does not resolve
